- Good morning.
- Hey.

2
00:04:16,178 --> 00:04:19,565
- Good morning.
- Hey.

3
00:04:19,566 --> 00:04:21,898
- Hey.
- Hi.

4
00:04:28,772 --> 00:04:29,858
- Dean Daniels?

5
00:04:29,859 --> 00:04:31,521
- That'd be me.

6
00:04:31,522 --> 00:04:34,007
- I got a note in my box that
said you wanted to see me.

7
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:38,585
- I sent out a lot of notes.

8
00:04:38,586 --> 00:04:40,854
I need you to tell me your name.

9
00:04:40,855 --> 00:04:42,484
- Oh, sorry.
Patrick Chibas.

10
00:04:42,485 --> 00:04:44,850
- Oh, Patrick.
Great.

11
00:04:44,851 --> 00:04:46,384
Come on in.

12
00:04:50,797 --> 00:04:53,002
How was your summer?

13
00:04:53,003 --> 00:04:55,334
- I waited tables
at this fusion place

14
00:04:55,335 --> 00:04:56,486
in the East Village.

15
00:04:56,487 --> 00:04:58,724
- Good money?
- Yeah.

16
00:05:00,770 --> 00:05:02,271
Am I in trouble?

17
00:05:02,272 --> 00:05:05,181
- No, no.
Not at all. No.

18
00:05:05,182 --> 00:05:08,185
You declared
an environmental sciences major

19
00:05:08,186 --> 00:05:09,176
last spring?

20
00:05:09,177 --> 00:05:10,646
- Yeah.

21
00:05:10,647 --> 00:05:13,716
- Well, we have a scholarship
that's designated for--

22
00:05:13,717 --> 00:05:15,089
well, it's designated

23
00:05:15,090 --> 00:05:17,007
for an outstanding
minority student

24
00:05:17,008 --> 00:05:18,318
in environmental sciences,

25
00:05:18,319 --> 00:05:20,429
and I just wondered
if you might be interested.

26
00:05:20,430 --> 00:05:21,546
- Sure.

27
00:05:21,547 --> 00:05:23,241
- Well,
there's just one thing then.

28
00:05:23,242 --> 00:05:24,360
I need to ask you, Patrick,

29
00:05:24,361 --> 00:05:26,470
On your Belmont application,
you--

30
00:05:26,471 --> 00:05:28,355
well,
under the voluntary disclosure

31
00:05:28,356 --> 00:05:30,050
of your racial/ethnic
background,

32
00:05:30,051 --> 00:05:32,639
you marked "other."

33
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:35,675
- Yeah.
I'm New Yorican.

34
00:05:35,676 --> 00:05:38,201
- New Yorican?
- Yeah.

35
00:05:38,202 --> 00:05:41,141
A New Yorker
of Puerto Rican descent.

36
00:05:41,142 --> 00:05:43,859
- Right.

37
00:05:43,860 --> 00:05:45,458
Do you think--
uh...

38
00:05:45,459 --> 00:05:47,407
would it be fair
for me to say, then,

39
00:05:47,408 --> 00:05:49,325
that you're hispanic?

40
00:05:49,326 --> 00:05:51,243
- What's wrong
with New Yorican?

41
00:05:51,244 --> 00:05:53,512
- Well, nothing,
of course.

42
00:05:53,513 --> 00:05:55,399
- Then why don't you
just say that?

43
00:05:55,400 --> 00:05:57,732
- Because the scholarship
committee is--

44
00:05:57,733 --> 00:06:02,271
well, they're not
culturally sensitive,

45
00:06:02,272 --> 00:06:04,637
if you know what I mean.

46
00:06:04,638 --> 00:06:05,852
- No.

47
00:06:05,853 --> 00:06:07,929
- They're old,
and, just trust me on this,

48
00:06:07,930 --> 00:06:09,943
the simpler the better
with these folks.

49
00:06:11,318 --> 00:06:13,075
- You do understand
why I don't want

50
00:06:13,076 --> 00:06:15,696
to be called hispanic,
don't you?

51
00:06:15,697 --> 00:06:16,751
- Well, as I understand it,

52
00:06:16,752 --> 00:06:18,255
and correct me,
please, if I'm wrong,

53
00:06:18,256 --> 00:06:20,173
it's because
it really only refers

54
00:06:20,174 --> 00:06:22,858
to imperialists
of European descent

55
00:06:22,859 --> 00:06:24,327
who colonized Puerto Rico.

56
00:06:24,328 --> 00:06:26,501
- Yeah, I mean,
if you understand, then--

57
00:06:26,502 --> 00:06:27,908
- Then why am I suggesting it?

58
00:06:27,909 --> 00:06:28,930
That's a good question.

59
00:06:28,931 --> 00:06:30,081
You're right.

60
00:06:30,082 --> 00:06:32,384
I shouldn't compromise
your feelings

61
00:06:32,384 --> 00:06:34,077
for the sake of expediency.

62
00:06:34,078 --> 00:06:35,260
I'm sorry.

63
00:06:35,260 --> 00:06:36,155
- That's okay.

64
00:06:37,370 --> 00:06:39,926
- How about
just plain Puerto Rican?

65
00:06:39,927 --> 00:06:40,982
- No.

66
00:06:40,983 --> 00:06:45,170
- It's a $12,000 scholarship,
Patrick.

67
00:06:45,171 --> 00:06:46,384
- It is?

68
00:06:46,385 --> 00:06:48,813
- You are a remarkably talented
student, Patrick,

69
00:06:48,814 --> 00:06:50,764
and I think
you should be rewarded

70
00:06:50,765 --> 00:06:52,617
in a meaningful way.

71
00:06:56,615 --> 00:06:58,211
- You can put "Puerto Rican."

72
00:06:59,235 --> 00:07:00,162
- Thank you.

73
00:07:02,751 --> 00:07:05,531
- # and that was just the way #

74
00:07:05,532 --> 00:07:08,504
# you play the game #

75
00:07:11,542 --> 00:07:12,595
- Fuck.

76
00:07:16,017 --> 00:07:17,167
- Dean Daniels.
- Yeah.

77
00:07:17,168 --> 00:07:18,701
- I'm Nathan Glazer, the R.A.

78
00:07:18,702 --> 00:07:20,235
Security's waiting inside.

79
00:07:20,236 --> 00:07:22,793
- And the student?
- Yeah.

80
00:07:22,794 --> 00:07:23,975
- What's his name?

81
00:07:23,976 --> 00:07:26,246
- Simon Brick.

82
00:07:26,247 --> 00:07:27,301
- Thanks.

83
00:07:35,741 --> 00:07:38,104
- They're right in here.

84
00:07:38,105 --> 00:07:40,598
- And neither of you guys heard
anything last night?

85
00:07:40,599 --> 00:07:41,684
Hey.

86
00:07:41,685 --> 00:07:42,675
- Oh, hello.

87
00:07:42,676 --> 00:07:45,425
Sarah, this is Jason...
- Thorn.

88
00:07:45,426 --> 00:07:46,959
- He found the note.

89
00:07:49,869 --> 00:07:51,435
- You must be Simon.

90
00:07:52,618 --> 00:07:53,831
- How'd you guess?

91
00:07:55,176 --> 00:07:58,211
- I'm Sarah Daniels,
the Dean of Students.

92
00:07:58,212 --> 00:07:59,810
Are you okay?

93
00:08:01,184 --> 00:08:02,366
- I guess.

94
00:08:02,367 --> 00:08:03,837
- What did the note say?

95
00:08:03,838 --> 00:08:05,978
Uh, <i>notes,</i> plural.

96
00:08:08,505 --> 00:08:10,198
- He found
the other one last week.

97
00:08:22,409 --> 00:08:24,007
- Why didn't you tell someone?

98
00:08:24,008 --> 00:08:26,213
- I just figured
some asshole put 'em there.

99
00:08:26,214 --> 00:08:28,003
- That's an understatement.

100
00:08:28,004 --> 00:08:29,058
This is serious shit.

101
00:08:29,059 --> 00:08:30,943
- I didn't want
to make a big deal.

102
00:08:30,944 --> 00:08:32,319
I just got here.

103
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:35,035
I don't want everyone
to know who I am like that.

104
00:08:35,035 --> 00:08:36,729
- So you don't have a roommate?

105
00:08:36,730 --> 00:08:37,688
- I live next door.

106
00:08:37,689 --> 00:08:38,839
- No, this is a single.

107
00:08:38,840 --> 00:08:40,182
- Did you request it?

108
00:08:40,183 --> 00:08:41,269
- Yeah.

109
00:08:41,270 --> 00:08:42,579
- You're lucky, man.

110
00:08:42,580 --> 00:08:44,305
My roommate stinks,
literally.

111
00:08:44,306 --> 00:08:45,264
His--his feet--

112
00:08:45,265 --> 00:08:46,990
- Okay.

113
00:08:48,718 --> 00:08:51,466
More to the point...

114
00:08:51,467 --> 00:08:52,809
we're gonna find out
who did this,

115
00:08:52,810 --> 00:08:55,717
and we're gonna put an end
to it.

116
00:08:59,682 --> 00:09:01,023
Would you like
to talk to somebody,

117
00:09:01,024 --> 00:09:02,877
maybe go see one
of the counselors

118
00:09:02,878 --> 00:09:04,252
over at Student Health?

119
00:09:06,618 --> 00:09:08,120
- You know,
I think I'd really just like

120
00:09:08,121 --> 00:09:09,207
to go to class.

121
00:09:13,075 --> 00:09:15,120
- If there's anything
that I can do,

122
00:09:15,121 --> 00:09:16,655
call me.

123
00:09:21,099 --> 00:09:22,313
Thank you.

124
00:09:22,314 --> 00:09:23,686
Thanks.

125
00:09:33,629 --> 00:09:35,930
- Has anyone had a run-in
with Simon?

126
00:09:35,931 --> 00:09:36,922
- The opposite.

127
00:09:36,923 --> 00:09:38,200
Everybody seems to like him.

128
00:09:38,201 --> 00:09:40,277
I made a point of asking him
to meals the first week

129
00:09:40,278 --> 00:09:41,524
since he didn't have a roommate.

130
00:09:41,525 --> 00:09:43,920
He's real shy.

131
00:09:43,921 --> 00:09:45,008
- Okay.

132
00:09:45,009 --> 00:09:47,789
Well, call us if you think
of anything.

133
00:09:47,790 --> 00:09:49,324
- You could, uh, put guards
at the doors

134
00:09:49,325 --> 00:09:51,721
is something I thought of.

135
00:09:51,722 --> 00:09:54,629
- Yeah, I'd have to clear it
with President Garvey.

136
00:09:54,630 --> 00:09:57,859
And tell your freshmen not
to prop the doors open, hmm?

137
00:09:57,860 --> 00:09:59,072
- Thanks, Nathan.

138
00:10:00,768 --> 00:10:02,078
Let's make copies
of those notes,

139
00:10:02,079 --> 00:10:04,348
and then you can give
the originals to the police.

140
00:10:04,349 --> 00:10:05,722
- You want me
to call the police?

141
00:10:05,723 --> 00:10:08,823
- Of course.

142
00:10:08,824 --> 00:10:10,101
What?

143
00:10:10,102 --> 00:10:13,426
- President Garvey will want
to handle it internally.

144
00:10:13,427 --> 00:10:15,726
- He's being threatened.

145
00:10:15,727 --> 00:10:17,103
- It's up to you.

146
00:10:20,395 --> 00:10:21,513
- Call the police.

147
00:10:21,514 --> 00:10:22,728
- Yes, ma'am.

148
00:10:24,679 --> 00:10:26,820
- These winter term classes
are an embarrassment.

149
00:10:26,821 --> 00:10:29,057
Wine tasting?

150
00:10:29,058 --> 00:10:31,007
The films of Brigitte Bardot?

151
00:10:31,008 --> 00:10:32,510
- I teach that.

152
00:10:32,511 --> 00:10:34,204
- Well, we can't be
too demanding

153
00:10:34,205 --> 00:10:35,514
in the winter term.

154
00:10:35,515 --> 00:10:36,889
- Why not?

155
00:10:36,890 --> 00:10:42,036
- Because it is one month
in the winter,

156
00:10:42,037 --> 00:10:45,392
and that's when they all ski,
all right?

157
00:10:45,393 --> 00:10:48,142
67% of students surveyed said
the ski slopes

158
00:10:48,142 --> 00:10:50,124
were a deciding factor
in choosing Belmont

159
00:10:50,125 --> 00:10:52,232
over competing colleges.

160
00:10:54,055 --> 00:10:55,013
You're late.

161
00:10:56,293 --> 00:10:57,762
- There's a problem.

162
00:10:57,763 --> 00:10:58,977
- God.

163
00:11:01,695 --> 00:11:03,964
- I have never seen anything
like this before.

164
00:11:03,965 --> 00:11:05,946
- Is he all right?
Is he frightened?

165
00:11:05,947 --> 00:11:09,078
- I mean, we might as well be
in Mississippi, 1963.

166
00:11:09,079 --> 00:11:13,746
All we need is guys with hoods
burning crosses on the quad.

167
00:11:13,747 --> 00:11:15,600
- Is that a plan?

168
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:16,975
- It had to be someone
from town.

169
00:11:16,976 --> 00:11:19,020
- Oh, because rural America
is racist?

170
00:11:19,021 --> 00:11:21,097
- Because it couldn't
be someone from here?

171
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:22,600
- What do we do?

172
00:11:22,601 --> 00:11:24,551
- President Garvey is speaking
in Boston.

173
00:11:24,552 --> 00:11:26,500
I can't call him
for another hour,

174
00:11:26,501 --> 00:11:29,792
so it gives us time
to come up with something.

175
00:11:32,510 --> 00:11:36,633
Jeffrey, give me Rita Chambers
in the press office.

176
00:11:36,634 --> 00:11:38,199
- I bet they don't do
a damn thing.

177
00:11:38,200 --> 00:11:40,213
- I bet they'll expel him.
- Or her.

178
00:11:40,214 --> 00:11:42,291
- We have to let people know
this isn't Belmont.

179
00:11:42,292 --> 00:11:44,241
We should issues some sort
of a statement right away

180
00:11:44,242 --> 00:11:45,648
condemning this.

181
00:11:45,649 --> 00:11:47,757
- Well, shouldn't we try
to find out who did it first?

182
00:11:47,758 --> 00:11:50,346
- They should have
an all-campus meeting,

183
00:11:50,347 --> 00:11:51,593
get it out in the open.

184
00:11:51,594 --> 00:11:52,552
- I bet you they call one

185
00:11:52,553 --> 00:11:54,629
of those useless
all-campus meetings.

186
00:11:54,630 --> 00:11:56,867
- An all-campus meeting.

187
00:11:56,868 --> 00:11:59,010
That feels like the kind
of response we should have.

188
00:11:59,011 --> 00:12:00,033
Doesn't it?
- Yeah.

189
00:12:00,034 --> 00:12:01,951
- In case any
of the parents call.

190
00:12:01,952 --> 00:12:04,507
- You could sell it
as a learning experience.

191
00:12:04,508 --> 00:12:06,297
- It is a learning experience.

192
00:12:06,298 --> 00:12:07,895
- And it will get everybody
on board, too,

193
00:12:07,896 --> 00:12:09,142
in terms of protecting the boy.

194
00:12:09,143 --> 00:12:10,804
- Like a neighborhood watch.

195
00:12:10,805 --> 00:12:11,763
- We'll cancel classes

196
00:12:11,764 --> 00:12:13,170
and hold the meeting
this afternoon.

197
00:12:13,171 --> 00:12:14,224
- I think we should wait.

198
00:12:14,225 --> 00:12:16,175
- Why don't we call it a forum?

199
00:12:16,176 --> 00:12:17,741
- A forum on race.
Good idea.

200
00:12:17,742 --> 00:12:20,107
- Wait, wait.
Wait a second.

201
00:12:20,107 --> 00:12:23,367
We should speak to Simon first.

202
00:12:23,368 --> 00:12:25,988
What if he doesn't want us
talking about him this way?

203
00:12:25,989 --> 00:12:26,947
- Why wouldn't he?

204
00:12:26,948 --> 00:12:28,673
- It might be embarrassing
for him.

205
00:12:28,674 --> 00:12:29,824
He's very quiet.

206
00:12:29,825 --> 00:12:31,390
Everybody will stare.

207
00:12:31,391 --> 00:12:32,956
- No one will stare.

208
00:12:32,957 --> 00:12:35,034
- Now, who's going to speak
at this forum.

209
00:12:35,035 --> 00:12:37,144
- You should, Catherine.
You're Dean of the College.

210
00:12:37,145 --> 00:12:38,455
- I'd like to put my name in.

211
00:12:38,456 --> 00:12:40,691
- You'll want
an African-American up there.

212
00:12:40,692 --> 00:12:42,609
- There's the chaplain.

213
00:12:42,610 --> 00:12:44,368
- Who else?

214
00:12:44,369 --> 00:12:46,159
- There's Ellen Jenkins
in Economics.

215
00:12:50,059 --> 00:12:51,177
Hmm.

216
00:12:55,110 --> 00:12:56,419
- Uh, Dean Kenney,

217
00:12:56,420 --> 00:12:58,337
One of the guys from
the police department's here,

218
00:12:58,338 --> 00:12:59,296
wants to talk to you.

219
00:12:59,297 --> 00:13:00,671
- The police?

220
00:13:00,672 --> 00:13:02,333
You called the police?

221
00:13:02,334 --> 00:13:04,124
- Yeah.

222
00:13:04,125 --> 00:13:05,850
- I told him to.

223
00:13:05,851 --> 00:13:07,352
- Never do that.

224
00:13:07,353 --> 00:13:09,333
It'll be in the local press,

225
00:13:09,334 --> 00:13:11,219
and then the wire services
will get hold of it,

226
00:13:11,220 --> 00:13:13,265
and then we're
everybody's business.

227
00:13:13,266 --> 00:13:14,577
How can you be so stupid?

228
00:13:14,578 --> 00:13:16,173
- Those notes are violent.

229
00:13:16,174 --> 00:13:17,836
- It is an internal incident.

230
00:13:17,837 --> 00:13:19,882
<i>Internal.</i>

231
00:13:19,883 --> 00:13:22,886
You have really overstepped
your bounds this time, Sarah.

232
00:13:22,887 --> 00:13:23,974
- Officer Olson wants--

233
00:13:23,975 --> 00:13:25,030
- Tell him to wait.

234
00:13:28,706 --> 00:13:30,879
I better not see any press
on this campus.

235
00:13:37,176 --> 00:13:39,285
- Hey.

236
00:13:39,286 --> 00:13:41,587
You did the right thing
calling the police.

237
00:13:41,588 --> 00:13:43,665
- You couldn't have said
that back there?

238
00:13:43,666 --> 00:13:46,957
- You still have the spark
of life left in you.

239
00:13:46,958 --> 00:13:48,172
Just give it a couple of years

240
00:13:48,173 --> 00:13:50,250
and you too will join the ranks
of the walking dead.

241
00:13:55,973 --> 00:13:58,401
Is that a reporter?

242
00:13:58,402 --> 00:14:00,863
Oh.

243
00:14:00,864 --> 00:14:02,013
- No.

244
00:14:02,014 --> 00:14:04,348
He just plays one on TV.

245
00:14:06,489 --> 00:14:07,672
- I don't know.

246
00:14:07,673 --> 00:14:09,685
I think the whole campus
is in shock, you know.

247
00:14:09,685 --> 00:14:11,187
- Mm-hmm.

248
00:14:11,188 --> 00:14:13,170
Are you in shock?

249
00:14:13,170 --> 00:14:14,129
- Well, yeah.

250
00:14:14,129 --> 00:14:15,599
Yeah, but I'm more curious,

251
00:14:15,600 --> 00:14:18,060
you know,
because historically speaking,

252
00:14:18,061 --> 00:14:20,777
<i>The Story of Little Black Sambo</i>
was a metaphor

253
00:14:20,778 --> 00:14:23,016
for imperialism
in East India, you know.

254
00:14:23,017 --> 00:14:24,133
So I'm wondering,

255
00:14:24,134 --> 00:14:28,418
well, when did Sambo come
to mean, um...

256
00:14:28,419 --> 00:14:30,432
oh, um, you know, I...

257
00:14:30,432 --> 00:14:32,189
- Sambo.

258
00:14:32,190 --> 00:14:33,340
- Sambo.
Yeah, Sambo.

259
00:14:33,341 --> 00:14:35,225
- Okay, can we please stop
saying "Sambo."

260
00:14:35,226 --> 00:14:37,304
- Excuse me.

261
00:14:37,305 --> 00:14:38,678
Hi.

262
00:14:40,085 --> 00:14:41,651
Can I help you?

263
00:14:41,652 --> 00:14:42,993
- I don't know.
Who are you?

264
00:14:42,994 --> 00:14:44,207
- I'm Sarah Daniels.

265
00:14:44,208 --> 00:14:45,902
I'm the Dean of Students.
Who are you?

266
00:14:45,903 --> 00:14:48,204
- Aaron Carmichael.

